  <article class="general-copy general-copy-about">
    <div class="header">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Our Story</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="main">
      <div class="container">
        <p>
          The single biggest impact the Internet has had is this: bringing people together to create things we couldn't have created alone. We can see this everywhere, from spaces like Wikipedia to the Open Source that runs most of the internet.
        </p>
        <p>
Assembly is a platform that enables anyone anywhere to openly collaborate and build real businesses together, just like the Internet intended. We're excited about what can be achieved as a connected community of millions of talented driven people are innovating on products freely.
        </p>

        <h2 class="excerpt-header text-light" style="background:url(/assets/about/excerpt-header1.jpg) center left no-repeat; background-size:cover;">
			Unlike traditional companies with shareholders and employees, everything on Assembly is created, operated, and owned by a global community of makers, together.
			
        </h2>
        <p>
          Assembly was built and launched in late 2013. In the short period Assembly has been running, we've already seen tens of thousands of strangers come together to build and launch products, middle schoolers coding next to seasoned designers, paid out thousands of dollars out to contributors on some of the early successful products, and seen millions of people use the products created by the community.		  
        </p>
        <figure class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6 left-offset caption-center">
          <img src="/assets/about/copy-img1.jpg">
          <figcaption></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <h3 style="margin-top:3.5rem;">
			Our Values
        </h3>
        <!-- <p>
          Acame up with our guiding principles, a set of ideals which we felt were key in defining Assembly as the place where great products could be built in this new way.
        </p> -->
		
		<p>
			<strong>Global Diversity.</strong>
			<br>
			Everyone is invited to make an impact, have influence, and be able to share their best work. Ideas, vision and execution are be driven by the community.
		</p>
		
		<p>
			<strong>Explicitness.</strong>
			<br>
			Leadership and vision are modeled after open source's notion of a merit-based Core Team that is part of the community.
		</p>
		
		<p>
			<strong>Liberty.</strong>
			<br>
		Instead of employment contracts, people should be able to work when they want, how they want, and where they want.
		</p>
		
		<p>
			<strong>Shared ownership.</strong>
			<br>
		Success is shared equitably. Each contribution should be rewarded with a fair amount of ownership stake as determined by the community.
		</p>

        <div class="row vertical-offset">
          <figure class="col-xs-12 col-md-8">
            <img src="/assets/about/copy-img2.jpg">
          </figure>
          <figure class="hidden-xs visible-md-block visible-lg-block col-md-4 caption-right">
            <img src="/assets/about/copy-img3.jpg">
            <figcaption></figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
        <h3 style="margin-top:3.5rem;">
		  The Team
        </h3>
		<p>
			We're commited to growing a team as diverse as our community. Those building Assembly include an engineer who studied the Latin American reception of ancient Greek tragedy, a physicist who studied nanometer scale biological self-assembly in confined lipid systems, and a writer who worked for The Daily Show with Jon Stewart. 
		</p>
        <p>
          Our current office is located in the heart of the Mission at <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/3030+16th+St,+San+Francisco,+CA+94103/@37.7652736,-122.4203596,17z/data=!4m7!1m4!3m3!1s0x808f7e23bb16b375:0xe81c0361915e031b!2s3030+16th+St,+San+Francisco,+CA+94103!3b1!3m1!1s0x808f7e23bb16b375:0xe81c0361915e031b" target="_blank">3030A 16th street in San Francisco</a>. We welcome anyone working on Assembly products to come visit us to work on your project out of our office.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

